    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.7.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 8.2.5141\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 10 (20H2)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal (1.13.11431.0); alacritty (0.10.1); neovim-qt (0.2.16.1)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nWindows Terminal: NULL; alacritty: xterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nchocolatey\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nStart nvim with minimal config:\r\n```vim\r\nset shell=pwsh.exe\\ -nop\r\n\" To effectively close terminal windows inside nvim, can be bound to any other keys\r\ntmap <silent> <space>t <C-\\><C-n>:q<CR>\r\n```\r\nCreate a new tab and open a terminal there:\r\n```vim\r\n:tabnew\r\n:terminal\r\n```\r\nThen, run some commands in the terminal. I run `ls` here, and here is how it looks:\r\n![297](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36408639/178025739-bc9f1707-7a3f-4fe2-9807-68fcaec1c09b.png)\r\nEverything is fine till now. But once `<space>t` (the key mapped in config file) is sent and reopen the terminal buffer in window with these commands:\r\n```vim\r\n:tabnew\r\n\" Check out the terminal buffer, the buffer id is 2 in this environment\r\n:buffer 2\r\n```\r\nthe contents of this buffer collapsed:\r\n![neovim-powershell-terminal-buf](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36408639/178026921-246756fd-c015-4a9c-91a4-4edd43008be9.gif)\r\nAs shown, at the second time I enter terminal mode, the cursor shows at upper area and then jumps to the bottom after I start typing, leaving a large blank area in this buffer.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nObviously, the contents in the terminal buffer should stay how it looks like when I left last time. The cursor should not jump, and the large blank area should not appear.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nAs described in *How to reproduce the issue* section. (Sry not following the report structure, because this bug is kinda weird and this is the best way I can describe it : (",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I found this issue when implementing VSCode-like terminal windows in nvim, and this can be avoid by adding blocking code in the *quick close* key mapping, for example:\r\n```vim\r\ntmap <space>t <C-\\><C-n>:exe \"sleep 100m \\| close\"<CR>\r\n```\r\nI guess it might be a latency-related issue?",
